documentTitle: Oochiumpa Good News Stories - Atnarpa Station Trip

participants.demographics: Young men plus one staff member

activities.description: Healing and connection to country day trip, including bush medicine demonstration, storytelling, and cooking kangaroo tails

outcomes.description: Malachi returned to his country and became involved with teaching visitors about his culture
Improved behavior through cultural connection and participation in cultural activities

keyQuotes: Two Cultures, One World, Working Together
It's not too late to learn these things of your family background and connection to country
successStories: Malachi has successfully reconnected with his country and culture, now participating in teaching visitors about his homelands and cultural knowledge
challenges: Initial disconnection from culture and country
Questions about family identity and connection to land
recommendations: Encourage ongoing cultural learning and connection to country
Support youth in reconnecting with their cultural heritage

documentTitle: Oonchiumpa Good News Stories - Fellas Day Trip to Standly Chasm

participants.demographics: Male youth participants (Darius Ross and Jayden White) with two mentors (Fred and Tyrone)

activities.description: Day trip to Standly Chasm with Aboriginal tour guides sharing cultural stories and visiting culturally significant sites

outcomes.description: Young participants exposed to Aboriginal tour guides and staff working on country in professional roles

keyQuotes: Two Cultures, One World, Working Together

This was a great activity/opportunity for the young fellers to hear from Aboriginal tour guides and see Aboriginal staff serving in the local café leading the way of what many Aboriginal People can do on the own lands.
successStories: Young participants were able to see positive role models of Aboriginal people working professionally on country through tour guides and café staff

documentTitle: Oonchiumpa Good News Stories - Girl Days Trip out Standly Chasm 29022024

participants.demographics: Female youth - July, Tyreena, Jonika and Henrisha

activities.description: Girls day out to Standly Chasm, viewing traditional owner management of country

outcomes.description: Girls gained exposure to successful Aboriginal land management by traditional owners
Participants opened up about their feelings during the trip

keyQuotes: Two Cultures, One World, Working Together
An opportunity to get out see the great work that other Aboriginal traditional owners are doing on their own land and making them feel empowered that they too can achieve the same goals
successStories: The girls were able to witness successful Aboriginal land management and feel empowered about their own potential
challenges: Very hot weather conditions during the trip

outcomes.description: Participants felt welcomed and enjoyed the hands-on food preparation experience

participants.demographics: Aboriginal Elders Aunty Bev and Uncle Terry sharing historical and cultural knowledge of Alice Springs

activities.description: Conversation about Alice Springs history, family stories, and cultural changes

outcomes.description: Detailed sharing of historical knowledge about Alice Springs, including WWII period, mission history, and cultural protocols

languages: multiple Aboriginal languages mentioned but not specified

keyQuotes: When we grew up, we knew, we grew up with two worlds - Aboriginal and Europeans
A lot of community people knew our family was the main family to Alice Springs
Dad could speak at least six or seven languages
successStories: Family maintaining strong cultural identity and knowledge across multiple generations
Four siblings reaching their 80s despite historical challenges
challenges: Modern youth disconnected from culture due to technology and social media
Lack of respect for elders among younger generation
Loss of traditional cultural knowledge transmission
recommendations: Need to preserve and pass on cultural knowledge to younger generations
Importance of maintaining traditional protocols and respect for country

activities.description: Sharing of Caterpillar Dreaming story and sacred sites knowledge

outcomes.description: Successful transmission of traditional stories about Caterpillar Dreaming, dog dreaming, and sacred sites to younger generations through schools

keyQuotes: these are really significant stories that we all grew up with learning and knowing and that what they teach in nowadays in school
the government were in consultation with the traditional owners with us, and, and in the middle of the night. They came and bulldozed the tail end of the, of the caterpillar.
successStories: Current generation able to challenge government decisions regarding sacred sites, unlike in the past
challenges: Historical destruction of sacred site (caterpillar tail) in 1982
Ongoing challenges with government regarding sacred sites and development
Past inability to challenge government decisions about sacred sites

participants.demographics: Law and public policy student at ANU

activities.description: Law student participation in cultural immersion and learning program

outcomes.description: Participant gained deeper understanding of Aboriginal conceptions of law and kinship systems

keyQuotes: I think the importance of culture, I think has been the main standout. It's been really incredible to be invited to immerse myself into a culture very different from my own.
Those are clearly born of, if not malicious intent, just negligent ignorance. And so, this kind of program would be so important for anyone going to a policy role or legal role in government.
successStories: Law student gained valuable cultural understanding and perspective transformation through program participation
recommendations: Program recommended for future government workers and policy makers

activities.description: Two 3-hour seminars discussing backgrounds and expectations
Visiting sacred sites with Traditional Owners

outcomes.description: Student reported exceeded expectations and gained deeper personal understanding of law and justice

keyQuotes: it makes law deeply personal and deeply relational
I'm really hoping that from this experience I can find a way to make the law more personal
a lot of people felt really disillusioned in their law degree because of the lack of grounding within the community
successStories: Law student gaining deeper understanding of true justice through on-country learning and connection with Traditional Owners
challenges: Feeling nervous due to unstructured nature of program compared to traditional law courses
Disillusionment with how law reduces people to categories

activities.description: Law student participating in ANU partnership program with Aboriginal elders and leaders

outcomes.description: Student reporting increased understanding and questioning of position within justice system after just two days
Student expressing desire to explore different ways of learning about law and seeking flexibility in legal thinking

keyQuotes: if this is just what two days of listening can achieve, imagine what a lifetime of deep listening can achieve
walk humbly with indigenous Australians and fight with indigenous Australians
We can bridge divides that exist currently by thinking more critically about steps forward
successStories: Law student finding new perspective on legal education through engagement with Aboriginal elders and deep listening practices
challenges: Initial barriers of uncertainty and unfamiliarity
Struggling to find passion and motivation in traditional legal career path
recommendations: Continue providing opportunities for law students to learn directly from Aboriginal elders and communities
Incorporate more flexible and open-minded approaches to legal education

participants.demographics: Law student from Australian National University

activities.description: Deep Listening on Country program with ANU law students

outcomes.description: Participant reported deeper understanding and meaningful knowledge transfer compared to traditional Western education
Student developed more nuanced understanding of Alice Springs and Aboriginal youth success stories

keyQuotes: These are two women who have, within 48 hours taught me, no offense, but more meaningful information and knowledge than I feel like I've gotten through all of my Western traditional structured schooling
It's just nice to be hearing stories from Tanya and Christie about aboriginal kids succeeding
successStories: Student demonstrated personal growth through repeated application process and gained deeper understanding of Aboriginal perspectives
challenges: Media propaganda and preconceptions about Alice Springs
Lack of public awareness about successful Aboriginal programs and outcomes
recommendations: Need for more visibility of positive Aboriginal community outcomes and success stories
Importance of self-directed learning rather than relying solely on Aboriginal people to educate

participants.demographics: Patricia Ann Miller - Traditional Owner, holds two doctorates and AO award

keyQuotes: If you know where you come from, people can't say 'why don't you get back to where you come from?' If they can't hunt us away from here, you're walking around our country, you are the guest.
They need good role models... sit down on country and also be with family. Where there's no alcohol or smoking and you go to bed when the sun goes down.
They just threw a blanket over everybody and said, we're putting this taken away the Racial discrimination Act and this was totally unfair to everybody.
successStories: Patricia Ann Miller served as deputy administrator for 20 years, worked with six administrators, met dignitaries including the royal family and Pope John Paul II
challenges: Tall Poppy syndrome affecting young women and men
Negative impacts of the 2007 intervention including job losses and removal of council member titles
Young people growing up in the city disconnected from culture
recommendations: Need to build profile and connections while managing community conflicts
Provide good role models for young people
Take young people on country to learn cultural rules and connect with family
Show young people that somebody cares about them

participants.demographics: High-risk young people in Central Australia

keyQuotes: We work with the most high risk young people in Central Australia and our role is twofold - as a cultural broker to link them and empower them in their identity as an Aboriginal person, and to bridge the gap between that aspect of who they are and the western world.
Working towards how we as an Aboriginal community bring back our lives, create something for our people to want to live for.

Community experiencing issues with racism, alcoholism, domestic violence
Lack of hope and opportunities for Aboriginal people
